<DOC><DOCNO> AP880517-0247 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-88 0121EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   05-17 0511</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0535</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Reagan administration working group on thestock market crash has issued a report recommending a variety ofmodest financial market changes aimed at preventing a recurrence oflast October's market crash.   The panel's major recommendation Monday was adoption of a``circuit breaker'' mechanism to shut down trading in the stock andfutures markets when extreme market movements threaten the entiresystem.   The panel said all trading should be halted for one hour on bothstock and stock index futures markets when the Dow Jones industrialaverage declines by 250 points from its closing level of theprevious day.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   U.S. industrial production surged 0.7 percentin April as a boom in demand for business equipment helped give thecountry the biggest increase in factory output in six months, thegovernment has reported.   The Federal Reserve said Monday that the April advance, morethan three times as rapid as the 0.2 percent March increase, pushedoverall industrial output 6.4 percent higher than a year ago.</TEXT><DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The biggest commercial airplaneorder in history has been split between Boeing Co. and AirbusIndustrie of Europe, with Boeing grabbing the lion's share of the$5.04 billion, 130-plane purchase by International Lease FinanceCorp.   The planes are to be delivered over the next six years toInternational Lease Finance, which leases planes to many of theworld's airlines for periods of three to 11 years.   Details of the order were released Monday.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Supreme Court has upheld a $1.8 millionjudgment against an insurance company that had been ordered to paythe money to an injured Mississippi man whose $20,000 claim itwrongfully rejected.   But the justices declined to decide the constitutionality oflarge punitive damage awards in personal injury cases.   In another case on Monday, the court ruled the FederalCommunications Commission has exclusive authority to regulate thetechnical quality of cable television signals.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Eastman Kodak Co. has agreed to reimburse atleast 4.2 million owners of its obsolete instant cameras as part ofa proposed $150 million settlement of a class action lawsuitagainst the company.   Under the settlement proposal Monday, U.S. owners of the cameraswould receive between $50 and $70 in cash and coupons.   Kodak stopped selling instant cameras and instant film after afederal court in 1985 said the company had violated patents held byPolaroid Corp.</TEXT><DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   E.F. Hutton andamp; Co. has paid $1.01 millionin fines for a money-laundering scheme in which $1.5 million incash was hidden from the government for clients, some of themmembers of organized crime.   Hutton attorney E. Lawrence Barcella Jr. signed a guilty plea tothree felony counts and turned a check for the fine over Monday toU.S. Attorney Lincoln C. Almond.   The brokerage company was fined $10,000 for conspiracy toviolate the Bank Secrecy Act and $500,000 for each of two counts ofviolating federal cash transaction reporting laws.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>